(75, 2, '2014-04-22 11:32:06', '2014-04-22 18:32:06', '<p style="text-align: center;"><a href="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-4.jpg"><img class="aligncenter wp-image-86" src="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-4.jpg" alt="deschutes-brewery-hopped-la" width="300" height="400" /></a></p>\r\nIn the west part of the San Fernando Valley, where quality craft beer is hard to come by, sits <a href="http://www.crazyharrysbar.com" target="_blank">Crazy Harry''s Bar</a> in the unassuming neighborhood of Winnetka. Crazy Harry''s opened a few year back much to my delight as well as others looking to saturate their tongues on something more complex and memorable than <a href="http://www.urbandictionary.com/define.php?term=Colorado%20Kool-Aid" target="_blank">Colorado Kool-aid</a>. Since then, this place has been my go-to spot for all things craft beer (<a title="Meet Vine 39, Tarzana’s Newest Craft Beer &amp; Wine Bar" href="http://localhost:8888/vine39-whole-foods-tarzana/" target="_blank">until my move to Tarzana introduced me to Whole Foods'' Vine 39</a>). My long-winded history with Crazy Harry''s Bar isn''t the point of this post, but rather to touch on their most recent event: The <a href="http://www.deschutesbrewery.com/" target="_blank">Deschutes Brewery</a> Tap Takeover.\r\n\r\nI showed up around 7pm, giving them a couple of hours to get ready for my arrival because, hey, I''m the prince of <a href="http://www.hoppedla.com" target="_blank">Hopped LA</a>. As expected, the bar manager, Jay, was serving this evening <span style="line-height: 1.5em;">and he came prepared with a few Deschutes favorites, including their new year-rounder, Fresh Squeezed IPA. I found my friend Kenny with some others at the end of the bar where I quickly made my way.</span>\r\n\r\n<img class="size-medium wp-image-80 alignleft" style="line-height: 1.5em;" src="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-2-e1398189047723-225x300.jpg" alt="deschutes-brewery-hopped-la" width="225" height="300" /><span style="line-height: 1.5em;">I had been looking forward to this moment all day, so I was salivating at the sight of Kenny''s Red Chair NWPA. Nevertheless, I followed the rule of never wrecking my palate too early and ordered a Mirror Pond Pale Ale from Jay.</span>\r\n\r\nI''ve always gotten on Harry''s for their marketing, or lack thereof, but they did a decent job of promoting the event. Hell, I even think I saw a sponsored post from <a href="http://www.facebook.com/crazyharrysbar" target="_blank">their Facebook page</a> popping up in my newsfeed the previous week. Additionally, they threw up some Deschutes label posters around the bar.\r\n\r\nAs time ticked on, my Mirror Pond came and went, and so did the Red Chair NWPA (which is delicious with its subtle caramel and grainy malt flavor). Then, I found myself ordering the Fresh Squeezed IPA and sitting next to the Deschutes LA Market Manager, Chelsea. She asked if I had tried it before, and I told her that I had during a recent trip to Flagstaff, AZ. With the melon and hop floral nose, and its juicy pineapple-orange taste, its a refreshing beer that you simply cannot go wrong with.\r\n\r\nAt this point, Jay was insisting that I sample the Mirror Mirror Barleywine, in which he boasts with his signature adjective: "phenomenal". At 11.2%, I''m glad it was just a sample because I was already feeling juiced up, however, I was able to extrapolate the different layers of this brew. <a href="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-3-e1398189202368.jpg"><img class="alignright size-medium wp-image-83" src="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-3-e1398189202368-225x300.jpg" alt="deschutes-brewery-hopped-la" width="225" height="300" /></a>Chelsea said the crew back in Oregon was really happy with the barleywine, but her personal favorite on the list was the Pinedrops IPA. Perfect timing, because that just so happened to be my next order.\r\n\r\nPinedrops is another brew I was able to try in Flagstaff, however, it was more interesting to learn from Chelsea that Harry''s had the ONLY keg of Pinedrops IPA in Los Angeles. Goes to show that Harry''s is no joke when it comes to getting great beer with somewhat exclusivity. Just last month, they tapped a cask of <a href="http://eaglerockbrewery.com/" target="_blank">Eagle Rock</a>''s Populist IPA brewed with Azacca hops that was prepared special for Crazy Harry''s. The Pinedrops poured a wonderful light gold, and instantly released its piney nose from the Chinook hops. It was also a bit fruity as well from other experimental hops that were thrown in. This is a solid beer that reigns in on the pine with a mouth full of hops, and I am looking forward to having more of it in the future.\r\n\r\nOverall, I had an excellent time at the Deschutes Brewery tap takeover, and was even able to leave with a new souvenir pint glass. I was also able to learn great things about Deschutes Brewery and can really appreciate their efforts in producing tasty, handcrafted beers. Thanks to Chelsea for the info, and to Harry and Jay for never putting crap on tap.\r\n\r\nWhat was the last tap takeover YOU went to, and what did you try? Let me know in the comments or on Twitter at <a href="http://www.twitter.com/hoppedla" target="_blank">@HoppedLA</a>.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-1.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-77" src="http://localhost:8888/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/photo-1.jpg" alt="deschutes-brewery-hopped-la" width="960" height="1280" /></a>', 'Deschutes Brewery Takes Over Crazy Harry''s Bar', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'deschutes-brewery-crazy-harrys-bar', '', '\nhttp://localhost:8888/vine39-whole-foods-tarzana/', '2014-04-22 20:05:41', '2014-04-23 03:05:41', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?p=75', 0, 'post', '', 1),
