(1931, 4, '2015-02-16 14:18:28', '2015-02-16 22:18:28', '<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-3.1.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1115" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-3.1.png" alt="Sweeneys-Ale-House-3.1" width="1200" height="628" /></a>If you''re a loyal reader of Hopped LA, then you know that we are scouring the city to bring you the best places to drink craft beer. Today is no different, friends, because <a href="http://www.sweeneysalehouse.com/" target="_blank">Sweeney''s Ale House</a> in Encino is the new kid on the block and you need to know about it. Sweeney''s has been open for a little over a month now, and I wanted to give them a bit of time to warm up to the community since my first visit during the "friends &amp; family" soft open when things were a bit shaky.\n\nSweeney''s Ale House first popped up on our <a title="Your Guide to the Best Beer Bars in the SFV (West)" href="http://hoppedla.com/best-beer-bars-in-the-sfv-west/" target="_blank">guide to the best beer bars in the West SFV</a>. Now that a solid chunk of time has passed (and we''ve actually been back several times), it''s time to give Sweeney''s the Hopped LA love it deserves.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/sweeneys-ale-house-5.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1121" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/sweeneys-ale-house-5.png" alt="sweeneys-ale-house-5" width="688" height="514" /></a>For me, accessibility and parking is a big deal for a potential gold mine on Ventura Blvd, and Sweeney''s Ale House actually makes it pretty easy with plenty of free parking in the back. Say ''sayonara'' to those parking meters. Once inside, you''ll notice that Sweeney''s is pretty expansive. Even if there''s nowhere to sit at the bar, you''re still not standing shoulder-to-shoulder with the group next to you.\n\nHere at Hopped LA, we''re obviously into the beer, and it''s nice to see that our boy, Ryan Sweeney, is still bringing in the good stuff. The focus of the tap list is noticeably diverse in style, but hop heads are bound to find something to soak their palates in.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-4.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1117" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-4.png" alt="Sweeneys-Ale-House-4" width="916" height="609" /></a>During the soft opening, I couldn''t stay away from Highland Park''s Neon IPA, Beachwood''s Laurel, and Ballast Point''s Grapefruit Sculpin. On my most recent visit, it was all about Bear Republic''s Apex and Saint Archer''s Double IPA. If you think you missed out on Grapefruit Sculpin, have no fear. As of this post''s publish, it''s currently waiting in the wings for another tapping, so I suggest heading over there sometime this weekend.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-Encino.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1118" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweeneys-Ale-House-Encino.png" alt="Sweeneys-Ale-House-Encino" width="917" height="626" /></a>The Irish nautical theme gives the space plenty of character, without being too over the top. It has a full bar for the cocktail and spirit drinkers with a heavy emphasis on Irish whiskey. They even have a couple draft cocktails, including their signature Dublin Donkey - their version of the Moscow Mule. If you come hungry, the Blue Fin Ahi Tuna Scoop, the Prosciutto Mac and Cheese, and the Pastrami Burger are all to-die-for. I also can''t forget to give a shout out to the bartenders and servers. They are all super-friendly and willing to give you the best experience possible.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweenys-Ale-House-2.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1119" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sweenys-Ale-House-2.png" alt="Sweenys-Ale-House-2" width="918" height="629" /></a>So, come for the food, come for the shuffleboard, but most of all, stay for the beer. Sweeney''s Ale House brings an excellent craft beer selection to a neighborhood of the San Fernando Valley that definitely needed it, bridging the gap between <a title="7 New Craft Beer Spots Putting Sherman Oaks on the Map" href="http://hoppedla.com/sherman-oaks-craft-beer/">Sherman Oaks'' restaurant row</a> and the West SFV.\n\nHave you visited Sweeney''s Ale House already? Let me know your thoughts in the comments below or on Twitter at <a href="http://www.twitter.com/hoppedla" target="_blank">@HoppedLA</a>. Or, let me know if you plan on getting your drink on over there soon. Perhaps, the Hopped LA bros will join you. Cheers!', 'Sweeney''s Ale House: The Best Place to Drink Craft Beer in Encino', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sweeneys-ale-house-encino', '', '', '2015-02-16 14:18:28', '2015-02-16 22:18:28', '', 0, 'http://hoppedla.com/?p=1111', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1932, 4, '2015-02-21 09:55:16', '2015-02-21 17:55:16', '<h6><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-1175" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/noble-ale-works-showers-series.png" alt="Noble Ale Works Showers Double IPA Series" width="1200" height="628" />\n<i>Top image credit: <a href="https://instagram.com/beer_spectator/" target="_blank">@beer_spectator</a></i></h6>\nThe SoCal beer community (and beyond) got a little anxious back in late 2013. Things were looking up for Anaheim-based <a href="http://www.noblealeworks.com/" target="_blank">Noble Ale Works</a> after taking 1st place at that year''s Los Angeles IPA Fest, and many eyes fell upon head brewer Evan Price to continue to deliver innovative and exciting IPAs.\n\nThen, came a beer forecast that would rain down exactly what hop-heads were looking for: the Showers Series, a locked Double IPA recipe that spotlighted one kind of hop per release, thus showcasing the unique aromatic and flavor qualities of each respective bud. And we were in love. Here''s the up-to-date, complete guide to the Noble Ale Works Showers Series.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Citra-showers-noble-ale-works1.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1149 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Citra-showers-noble-ale-works1.png" alt="Citra-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="549" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Citra Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: December 2013</em>\n\nCitra hops are by far one of my favorites, and the mere mention of this beer caused an enormous amount of salivation. It was a great one to begin the Shower Series adventure because it set a precedent for each subsequent release that almost made it mandatory for IPA lovers to try each one. Citra Showers poured a wonderful glowing, golden amber hue with a head that caked on top. One sniff of this bad boy and your nose was filled with tropical fruit with obvious mango and grapefruit undertones and finished with a crisp malt bill. The taste was no different. It was fresh and fruity, offered hints of bubblegum, and was complemented with a dry and bitter backend.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.59.24-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1153" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.59.24-PM.png" alt="nelson-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="396" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Nelson Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: January 2014</em>\n\nThe following month brought Nelson Showers. This New Zealand varietal is quite the mind bender where it''s described as producing flavors of Sauvignon Blanc, gooseberries, truffle, and allspice. The aroma was an awesome blend of grapefruit and dankness with a mouth full of tropical sweetness. Don''t let that last word discourage the hop profile, as it was extremely well balanced with the malt.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.32.37-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1155" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.32.37-PM.png" alt="amarillo-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="547" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Amarillo Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: February 2014</em>\n\nAmarillo poured a slight murky orange with a soapy white head that thinned out fairly quickly. The thing I look out for in amarillo hops is that aroma and flavor of orange peel/flesh that ends up catering to the grassy yet tropical back-end. This one finished with a bit of pine that sat on my tongue for a little while, but left something else to be desired.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.32.21-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1160" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-9.32.21-PM.png" alt="simcoe-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="417" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Simcoe Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: March 2014</em>\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/spring-forecast-simcoe-showers/" target="_blank">Simcoe</a> was a bit of a relief from the previous month''s Amarillo release because the tropical notes carried through the pine a bit better on this one. And when you''re presented with that kind of beer that''s supplemented with orange peel, passion fruit, and mango, you can''t go wrong. The dankness develops as the tasting progresses, but I wasn''t complaining.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/tba-equinox-showers-noble-ale-works.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1161" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/tba-equinox-showers-noble-ale-works.jpg" alt="tba-equinox-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="409" /></a>\n<h2><strong>TBA (Equinox) Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: April 2014</em>\n\nWe were all waiting patiently until the hop varietal was announced for this one. In the meantime, I was greeted with a nose full of cantaloupe and a hint of pineapple, but the taste didn''t add up. I mean, the initial hop profile was there, but wasn''t super strong and the malt character was barely there. Not a huge complaint given that I don''t like a strong malt background, so overall the beer was quality and had a crisp finish.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-11.35.35-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1163" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-20-at-11.35.35-PM.png" alt="Rakau-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="405" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Rakau Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: May 2014</em>\n\nThis one poured a slight hazy yellow with some aromas of citrus, floral notes, and pine. The taste was very similar to the aroma, however, it introduced a hint of caramel to the equation. This is another one that capped off with a dry finish. Overall, a good balance between hops and malt.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.06.14-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1165" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.06.14-AM.png" alt="el-dorado-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="419" /></a>\n<h2><strong>El Dorado Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: June 2014</em>\n\nI got a lot of citrus, orange, and pine off the nose on this one, which is always nice. The taste a caramel backbone that lent sweetness to the entire body, but was still light and offered bit of dankness. I''m thinking that I waited a little too long to crack this one open, so something tells me I would''ve liked it a lot of more had I poured it sooner. Still, a nice effort.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.27.05-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1166" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.27.05-AM.png" alt="chinook-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="416" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Chinook Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: August 2014</em>\n\nThis hazy amber pour delivered a puffy off-white head that left a generous amount of lacing on the glass. This one was very piney with hints of citrus, and I''m talking resinous pine with a oily mouthfeel. The flavor was pretty light, and while it''s not my favorite one, Noble did a good job highlighting this particular varietal.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.33.15-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1167" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-7.33.15-AM.png" alt="galaxy-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="407" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Galaxy Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: September 2014</em>\n\nGalaxy Showers was a nice comeback from the last release, shining with distinct grassy, citrusy, and piney vibrancy. This one did a really good job and highlighting the unique qualities of the galaxy hop. It was fresh and bright with a dry, rustic finish that added a hint of sweetness for balance. This was a good one in my book.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.22.45-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1170" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.22.45-AM.png" alt="waimea-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="409" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Waimea Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: November 2014</em>\n\nWaimea Showers was an interesting release due to the pungent onion notes that I picked up from the aroma. The subtle pine and passionfruit helped balance it out, while the taste was lightly sweet with some dankness. These releases tend to hide the alcohol and malt well giving this one a medium body and making it pretty drinkable.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.33.15-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1171" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.33.15-AM.png" alt="mosaic-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="406" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Mosaic Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: December 2014</em>\n\nI''m actually a big fan of mosaic hops, and it''s nice to see that it made an appearance, albeit a late one. This was one hop bomb of mango, watermelon, and juicy fruit with a very pale malt background. It''s not overly complex, which is what I like about it. I picked up some of the alcohol, but it was welcomed warmth and didn''t sit for too long. The tropical notes take center stage on this one.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.40.31-AM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1172" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-9.40.31-AM.png" alt="sorachi-ace-showers-noble-ale-works" width="409" height="545" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Sorachi Ace Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: January 2015</em>\n\nSorachi Ace Showers was advertised as being "different", so naturally, I was excited to see what this release was all about. I will say that it wasn''t quite what I was expecting, and in fact, I was less of a fan than Gary was. It was hard for me to pick up the dill until later in my tasting experience, but it was there. I was also getting a bit of cotton candy, which came out of nowhere (this was a note that Gary was not picking up). Overall, there were big tropical components which I liked, but I won''t be dying for this one again.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-07-20-at-8.05.38-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1408" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-07-20-at-8.05.38-PM.png" alt="Wakatu-showers-noble-ale-works-showers-series" width="409" height="410" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Wakatu Showers</strong></h2>\n<em>Release Date: June 2015</em>\n\nWakatu Showers was one of the more interesting releases due to the unique hop profile of berries, citrus, melon, and tropical fruit. Like any Showers release, the hop flavors are strong and are finished by a light alcohol bite to provide a little warmth. The juiciness of this release cannot be denied and makes this one an enjoyable beer when it''s fresh. The flavor profile does change quite a bit as the beer ages, but that''s to be expected.\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/blanc-showers.jpg"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1735" style="border: 3px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/blanc-showers.jpg" alt="blanc-showers" width="800" height="800" /></a>\n<h2>Blanc Showers</h2>\n<em>Release Date: September 2015</em>\n\nBlanc Showers was an interesting release that featured <span data-reactid=".1.1.0.0.2.1.0.0.1"><span data-reactid=".1.1.0.0.2.1.0.0.1.0">German Hallertau Blanc hops. The pour was your typical hazy golden orange like the rest of the Showers with upfront flavors of sweet, fresh fruit. With a sting of citrus and a balanced malt character to round it out, I''d say Blanc Showers was a very nice release.</span></span>\n\nI''ll continue to update this if more new Showers Series are released. Quite a few versions have been back for reprisals already, and I''m expecting others to see additional life. It''s great to see this kind of experimentation that ultimately led to Noble Ale Works'' conception of I Love It! IPA which, of course, took 1st place at LA IPA Fest 2014. Gotta love those back-to-back wins, and the mission to bring great craft beer to the people who love it.\n\nWhat is your favorite Noble Ale Works Showers Series release? Let me know in the comments or on Twitter at <a href="http://www.twitter.com/hoppedla" target="_blank">@HoppedLA</a>.\n\n&nbsp;', 'The Complete Guide to the Noble Ale Works Showers Series', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'noble-ale-works-showers-series', '', '', '2015-02-21 09:55:16', '2015-02-21 17:55:16', '', 0, 'http://hoppedla.com/?p=1136', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1933, 4, '2015-03-09 08:03:35', '2015-03-09 15:03:35', 'You knew it was on the horizon when the "Coming Soon" banners went up around the exterior perimeter of the space formerly occupied by Sisley Italian Restaurant. You waited patiently as Winter 2014 came and went without a word on the opening after reading about it on <a title="7 New Craft Beer Spots Putting Sherman Oaks on the Map" href="http://hoppedla.com/sherman-oaks-craft-beer/" target="_blank">our last piece about craft beer in Sherman Oaks</a>. And, finally, the craft beer fiend inside of you became thrilled when it surfaced that Public School 818 was opening in March 2015. Okay, maybe I''m describing myself, but I know you shared the same sentiments, and Hopped LA has come to let you know that...<em>it''s here. </em>\n\n<a href="http://psontap.com/locations/ps818/" target="_blank">Public School 818</a> is now open in Sherman Oaks and it''s everything we hoped it would be. The schoolhouse theme is executed perfectly in a upscale, yet casual, space with all sorts of trinkets adorning the walls and shelves instead of the classroom. If you''ve been to a Public School before, then you know the drill.\n\nIt wasn''t my first time at a PS, but it was great to hear our server, Adam, break down what this place is all about with emphasis on the fresh quality. The scratch bar and kitchen means you''re getting pretty much everything made in-house, even down to the bitters inside their Lavender Vanilla cocktail (house-made vanilla bitters, lavender simple syrup, Four Roses Small Batch).\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-14.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1207" style="border: 2px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-14.png" alt="public-school-818-14" width="600" height="451" /></a>\n<h2><strong>The Space</strong></h2>\nOne of the first things that you notice when approaching the entrance is the expansive patio with a fire pit. Perfect for a cool summer evening, you ask? You betcha. Walking in, you''re greeted by letterman jackets hanging on the coat rack with a large L-shaped bar taking centerstage just beyond that. Cozy leather booths fill up the middle of the space with larger circular tables stationed just in front of the glass windows that look into the kitchen.\n\nMy favorite part about the space is the unassuming door next to the bar that opens up into the private dining room titled "The Rec Room". In addition to providing darts and Jenga for you and your friends, the room also has a large projection screen and will be holding beer &amp; cocktail education classes. So far, this is the only Public School to have a Rec Room, but we''ll see what they do with their upcoming openings in Las Vegas and Addison, Tx.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-3.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1221" style="border: 2px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-3.png" alt="public-school-818-3" width="500" height="375" /></a>\n<h2><strong>The Bar</strong></h2>\nPublic School''s Beverage Director, Colin, came by the table to talk a little about the program and how the community gets to have a hand in some of the great output. For instance, their house IPA called "School House IPA" is brewed by <a href="http://www.figmtnbrew.com/" target="_blank">Figueroa Mountain Brewing Co.</a>, who we know is starting their expansion into Westlake Village. This American IPA has a big hop presence, but is really well-balanced by a sweet malt finish. Turns out the sweetness is added by champagne grapes, while the malts are roasted by a local coffee roaster.\n\nNext, their resident "beer geek" (their words, not mine), Andrew, stopped by to deliver tastings of some of the special beers they have on tap for opening week. Of course, I''m a hop head, but Ladyface''s 5th Anniversary Ale and The Lost Abbey''s Bat Out Of Hell seemed to sit very well on the palate. Big brews with lasting impressions, that''s for sure. It was nice hearing Andrew talk about his appreciation for fresh hops as well as his love for brews that are barrel aged. As sour beers get more and more popular in this part of LA, he expects to ramp up the sour offering at Public School 818 as well. He also emphasized the twenty-four taps, with twelve being the core beers that rotate four times a year and twelve that rotate constantly all year long. We soaked our tongues in Bell''s Two-Hearted Ale, Ballast Point''s Grunion, and Two-Five Left and Blue House Citra from local boys, El Segundo Brewing, but looking forward to seeing what PS818 puts on next.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-15.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1217" style="border: 2px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/public-school-818-15.png" alt="public-school-818-15" width="500" height="334" /></a>\n<h2><strong>The Food</strong></h2>\nThis occasion made it easy for us to decide to order some things that we normally wouldn''t try. That resulted in a tender Flat Iron Steak with Mac and Cheese, hearty Chicken and Waffles, and a delectable serving of Shrimp &amp; Grits made with St. Archer White Ale. Executive Chef Phil Kastel mentioned a few other dishes that were made with beer, so it''s great to learn about that incorporation. Adam made sure our table was fully covered as well by letting us try out their Bacon Cheddar Tots with Sriracha honey ketchup (awesome) and their house pepperoni pizza (also awesome). To say we were full is an understatement.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Screen-Shot-2015-03-08-at-11.39.25-PM.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-1223" style="border: 2px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Screen-Shot-2015-03-08-at-11.39.25-PM.png" alt="public-school-818-16" width="600" height="259" /></a>\n<h2><strong>Time for Recess</strong></h2>\nOne thing to note are the beer prices, namely the ones that were on the rotating list. I know that paying eleven or twelve bucks for a pour sounds ridiculous, but we''re mindful of the special brews they chose to open their doors with. For those of you who want to get your drink on while not fully breaking the banks, consider checking them out during Recess time, which is their version of happy hour. From 4pm - 7pm Monday to Friday, it''s Recess in the bar at Public School 818 where many food items can be consumed at a good price, and you''re drinking great beers for $4 or $5. Not too shabby, right?\n\nWe were happy to give Public School 818 the Hopped LA welcome that it deserves, as it joins the SFV craft beer community. Speaking of SFV and community, there''s even a vintage style map on the wall of the SFV plotted with the locations of all the major public schools in the area. Many thanks to the PS818 team. You guys rock! Now, go gather some friends, pull up a chair, and grab a pint at Public School 818 because class is now in session.\n<h2><strong>Public School 818</strong></h2>\n<div><strong>15300 Ventura Blvd. #102G</strong></div>\n<div><strong>Sherman Oaks, Ca 91403</strong></div>\n<div><strong>(818) 728-9818</strong></div>\n<div></div>\n[slideshow_deploy id=''1243'']', 'Now Open: Public School 818 in Sherman Oaks', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'now-open-public-school-818-sherman-oaks', '', '', '2015-03-09 08:03:35', '2015-03-09 15:03:35', '', 0, 'http://hoppedla.com/?p=1202', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(1934, 4, '2015-05-06 21:51:14', '2015-05-07 04:51:14', 'For the 6th year running now, the <a href="http://www.veganbeerfest.com/" target="_blank">Los Angeles Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival</a> is kicking off on Saturday May 16th at 1pm at the Rose Bowl in Pasadena. This event has some humble beginnings, launching its first year in the parking lot of The Roxy in West Hollywood in 2009 before selling out the last 4 years and being forced to upgrade location capacity.\n\nWhy should you go to a vegan beer and food festival, you ask? Well, since this will be my first year attending, I can''t tell you about some awesome past experience that I''ve had there. But I''ve scoped all the details, and I wanna let you know why the Los Angeles Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival has the makings to be one of the better beer festivals thrown in LA all year.\n<h3><strong><img class="alignnone wp-image-1305 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/rosebowl-resized.jpg" alt="LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival 2015 at the Rose Bowl" width="600" height="338" />\n1. The Location</strong></h3>\nFirst off, it''s at the freakin'' Rose Bowl in beautiful Pasadena. It doesn''t get much better than that. There will be plenty of room to hang with your group comfortably, drink great beer &amp; munch on some tasty vegan food. Plus, unlike a lot of other beer festivals in LA, the Rose Bowl has permanent restrooms that are built to accommodate massive crowds. Yep, you won''t be making multiple 30 minute trips to the porta potty line at this event.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3><strong>2. The Organizers</strong></h3>\nSecond, the organizers of this event KNOW THEIR SHIT. Nic Adler, owner of The Roxy, is handling the music. Tony Yanow of Tony''s Darts Away / Mohawk Bend / Golden Road Brewing is handling the beer. QuarryGirl, an influential vegan food blogger is handling the food. And also a part of the organizer mix is Goldenvoice…ever heard of em? Yep, they not only put on the massively popular Coachella Music Festival every year, but they also operate a bunch of awesome LA venues like the Fonda, the El Rey, Shrine Auditorium, Club Nokia and Nokia Theatre LA Live. It''s almost like this event is guaranteed NOT to suck.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3><strong>3. The Music</strong></h3>\nOk, so I personally haven''t heard of any of the bands taking the stage at this year''s LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Fest, but there''s nothing better than sipping delicious craft beer and sampling awesome vegan food with some live music in the background. The bands all sound more rock &amp; folk focused, which is sure to provide a nice backdrop to the festivities at the Rose Bowl that day. And if you''re so inclined, give the headliners a little preview listen: <a href="https://www.facebook.com/jamestownrevival" target="_blank">Jamestown Revival</a>, <a href="https://www.facebook.com/thewhitebuffalomusic" target="_blank">The White Buffalo</a>.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3><strong><img class="alignnone wp-image-1303 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/veganbeerfest-924852829118304984_368521827-e1430974246169.png" alt="Doomie''s Big Mac - LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival" width="550" height="550" />\n4. The Food</strong></h3>\nI''ll start this off by saying I am not a vegan. Nope, not even close. BUT, that doesn''t mean I won''t eat vegan food. Especially if it''s that recreated Big Mac from Doomie''s Home Cookin'' in Hollywood. In addition to Doomie''s, there will be about 40 other food vendors in attendance, including Mudhen Tavern, M Cafe, Donut Fiend, and the Grilled Cheese Truck. Unfortunately tickets don''t include food, so be sure to bring some cash so you can sample some of that awesome vegan grub.\n\n&nbsp;\n<h3><strong><img class="alignnone wp-image-1304 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/VeganBeerFestEB.jpg" alt="Beer Taster at LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival" width="2000" height="1351" />\n5. The Beer</strong></h3>\nLast, but certainly not least, you''re really going to the LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival for the beer. Over 100 different beers from over 65 breweries will be pouring, many of which will be local LA breweries. Some of our favorites include Ohana, King Harbor, Modern Times, Noble Ale Works, Ballast Point, El Segundo, Karl Strauss, Pizza Port, and Three Weavers. Plus, you''ll get a special 4oz LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival 2015 tasting glass to sample unlimited beers and take home with you at the end of the day.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nConvinced yet? Good! The LA Vegan Beer &amp; Food Festival kicks off at 1pm on Saturday May 16th, 2015. Tickets at the door will be $65, but they''re only $50 if you buy them online in advance. So <a href="http://www.ticketfly.com/event/785917" target="_blank"><strong>grab yours now before they sell out</strong></a>!', '5 Reasons You Should Attend the LA Vegan Beer & Food Festival 2015', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'la-vegan-beer-food-fest-2015', '', '', '2015-05-06 21:51:14', '2015-05-07 04:51:14', '', 0, 'http://hoppedla.com/?p=1302', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(1935, 4, '2015-06-11 22:20:00', '2015-06-12 05:20:00', '<img class="alignnone wp-image-1337 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/karl-strauss-cw-exterior3-e1434084069685.png" alt="Karl Strauss CityWalk" width="700" height="394" />Chances are, when you think of all the LA breweries pumping out awesome beer, Karl Strauss might not be one that comes to mind. Sure, they''re based out of San Diego and their LA location is smack dab in a place most of us locals usually never set foot - the tourist trap of Universal CityWalk. But if you''ve been overlooking Karl Strauss'' LA offering, you''ve been missing out on some seriously awesome beer. For LA Beer Week, we teamed up with the Karl crew in LA and brewed up a new reason for Los Angeles to start paying attention.\n\nWhile Karl''s production brewery in San Diego is their main show, don''t think they left their remote LA location in the hands of some inexperienced amateur brewer. No, their LA brewery is manned by none other than Karl Strauss brewmaster, Paul Segura, a 20+ year brewery veteran responsible for countless award-winning beers.\n\nPaul makes the trek up to LA about once a month to personally brew CityWalk''s monthly "Tank Tap" beer, a rotating specialty beer brewed exclusively at and for the CityWalk location. Last month''s Tank Tap was a deliciously hoppy Pale Lager called Citranaut, brewed exclusively with - you guessed it - the amazing Citra hops.\n\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-1343 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/karl-strauss-hops-e1434084663517.png" alt="Karl Strauss Hops" width="700" height="463" />This month''s Tank Tap is an extra special one. Mack and I teamed up with the Karl Strauss crew to brew a beer in honor of LA Beer Week. We wanted to deliver something that we felt really fit the LA personality. A beer with a light body, high drinkability, and a platform to showcase a strong West Coast hop profile. With that direction, Paul put together a killer recipe for an India Pale Lager brewed with Chinook, Citra, and Mosaic hops, dry-hopped with even more Mosaic.\n\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-1344 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/karl-strauss-mack-brian-mash-e1434085160447.png" alt="Karl Strauss CW Mash" width="700" height="467" />On May 12, Mack and I met up at Karl''s LA brewery with Paul, Brian and Ryan from the Karl Strauss marketing team, and Chris, Kelly, and Robert from the Karl Strauss LA sales team and put Paul''s recipe to work. On that day, our hoppy homage to the LA beer community, Hoppywood &amp; Bine, was born. The final product packs a ton of hoppy bitterness on a light body and will be officially tapped on June 19th at <a href="https://www.facebook.com/events/1615669838689098/" target="_blank">our LABW Preview &amp; release event at City Tavern in Culver City</a>. Hoppywood will also be available at our <a href="https://www.facebook.com/events/481082658708035/" target="_blank">Special LABW IPA Night on June 23rd at Crazy Harry''s Bar in the Valley</a> as well as all the beer bars listed below throughout LA Beer Week. Here''s to you, LA hop heads!\n\n<img class="alignnone wp-image-1340 size-full" style="border: 1px solid #000000;" src="http://hoppedla.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/karl-strauss-mack-gary-paul2-e1434084273676.png" alt="Mack &amp; Gary Magnone with Paul Segura" width="700" height="446" />\n\nYou can find the Karl Strauss / Hopped LA collaboration Hoppywood &amp; Bine India Pale Lager on tap starting June 19th at the following locations:\n\n<strong>Kings Row Gastropub in Pasadena</strong>\n<strong>Far Bar in Little Tokyo</strong>\n<strong>Buzz Wine Beer Shop in DTLA</strong>\n<strong>Spring St. Smokehouse in Chinatown</strong>\n<strong>The Republic in Covina</strong>\n<strong>Link in Beverly Hills</strong>\n<strong>Rose City Pizza in Alhambra</strong>\n<strong>Dog Haus Biergarten in Pasadena</strong>\n<strong>Matt Denny''s Ale House in Arcadia</strong>\n<strong>Old Towne Pub in Pasadena</strong>\n<strong>Slaters 50/50 in Pasadena</strong>\n<strong>Public School (multiple locations)</strong>\n<strong>Tender Greens in Hollywood</strong>\n<strong>Whole Foods (multiple locations)</strong>\n<strong>City Tavern in Culver City</strong>\n<strong>Naja’s Place in Redondo Beach</strong>\n<strong>Select Beer Store in Redondo Beach</strong>\n<strong>Lucky''s Tavern in Hollywood</strong>\n<strong>Tony''s Darts Away in Burbank</strong>\n<strong>Taps Valley Gastropub in Northridge</strong>\n<strong>Crazy Harry''s Bar in Winnetka</strong>', 'Brewing Hoppywood: An LA Beer Week Collaboration with Karl Strauss', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'hoppywood-and-bine', '', '', '2015-06-11 22:20:00', '2015-06-12 05:20:00', '', 0, 'http://hoppedla.com/?p=1331', 0, 'post', '', 2);
